[3] Cholera - Sierra Leone (Freetown)
Date: Sun, 22 Oct 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Pan African News Agency [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LZEG-6URRNE?OpenDocument>

An official at the ministry of health and sanitation disclosed on
Thu, 19 Oct 2006 that 74 persons have died from a cholera outbreak
that has also left 1114 others affected in Freetown. Health education
officer, Lansana Conteh said the Disease Prevention and Control
officer, Dr. Alhasan Sesay confirmed the outbreak, after a laboratory
test was done on feces samples in Ghana.
Conteh said the outbreak is more prevalent in the eastern part of
Freetown whereas few cases have been reported in the central and west
of the capital. He also confirmed the presence of cholera in the
northern rural districts of Kambia and Tonkolili.
Meanwhile, emergency health centers have been set up and with the
help of WHO, UNICEF and other healthcare partners, volunteers have
been trained to sensitize local communities about the outbreak, and
how to avoid being infected.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
